    background: 'OVHIPEC-1 proved a benefit for HIPEC at interval surgery, but many patients undergo primary complete debulking without neoadjuvant chemotherapy. It was unknown whether the HIPEC advantage extends to the upfront-surgery setting, where tumour burden and operative morbidity differ.',
    design: 'Multicentre randomised phase III trial in the primary-surgery population, using the OVHIPEC-1 cisplatin protocol; PFS as the primary endpoint with OS follow-up ongoing.',
    results_detail: 'Preliminary reporting suggested a progression-free survival signal favouring HIPEC (approximate median PFS 16.8 vs 12.3 months, HR ~0.73), consistent with the biological rationale, but overall survival data were immature at the time of first presentation. Toxicity in the primary-surgery setting was higher than at interval surgery given the larger operations, without prohibitive safety concerns.',
    practice_change: 'If confirmed with mature OS data, OVHIPEC-2 would extend the HIPEC indication from interval to primary ovarian cancer surgery, potentially supporting cisplatin HIPEC across all cytoreductive time points. Until then, OVHIPEC-1 (interval setting) remains the established, guideline-supported evidence base.',
