    results_detail: 'BAP1-mutated/haploinsufficient tumours showed markedly better survival (median OS not reached at 5 years) than BAP1-wild-type (median OS ~28 months, p≈0.003) — the opposite prognostic direction to some pleural data. Germline BAP1 alterations were found in ~13% of patients, defining a hereditary cancer-predisposition subset (BAP1 tumour predisposition syndrome) warranting counselling. BAP1 loss also has implications for immunotherapy responsiveness.',
    practice_change: 'Established BAP1 as a prognostic biomarker specific to peritoneal mesothelioma and mandated routine BAP1 (and germline) testing with genetic counselling. It reframed BAP1-loss disease as a favourable-prognosis, immunogenic subset, informing surveillance for hereditary syndrome and the design of immune-checkpoint therapy in mesothelioma.',
    criticisms: 'Retrospective, modest single-institution cohort with potential selection bias; the cited genome-medicine work is mechanistic/associative rather than a randomised prognostic validation. BAP1 assay methods (IHC vs sequencing) and thresholds vary. Prognostic direction and germline frequency require external validation.',
    evidence_level: 'IIb',
    study_type: 'retrospective',
