    key_result: 'Median OS 11.0 vs 6.5 months (HR 0.73; p=0.046) favouring CRS+HIPEC (cisplatin 120 mg + mitomycin C 30 mg, 43°C, 60–90 min) over CRS alone. Serious adverse-event rates were comparable between arms. The first randomised evidence that HIPEC adds survival benefit to cytoreduction in gastric peritoneal metastases.',
    practice_impact: 'Landmark trial from the Chinese peritoneal surface oncology programme (Yan Li group, Beijing). Established proof-of-principle for CRS+HIPEC in gastric PM and anchored subsequent Chinese consensus guidelines; remains a pivotal randomised reference for HIPEC in gastric carcinomatosis and underpins ongoing confirmatory trials (GASTRICHIP, GASTRIPEC-I).',
    pico: {
      population: '68 patients with peritoneal carcinomatosis from gastric cancer undergoing cytoreductive surgery at a single Chinese centre.',
      intervention: 'Cytoreductive surgery plus HIPEC (cisplatin 120 mg + mitomycin-C 30 mg, 43 °C, 60–90 min).',
      comparator: 'Cytoreductive surgery alone.',
      outcome: 'Primary endpoint: overall survival; secondary: safety and prognostic factors.',
    },
    background: 'Gastric peritoneal carcinomatosis carried a median survival of only a few months with any treatment. Single-arm and Japanese data suggested intraperitoneal chemotherapy might help, but no randomised trial had tested whether adding HIPEC to cytoreduction improved survival — the question this first phase III RCT addressed.',
    design: 'Single-centre, prospective, randomised phase III trial allocating patients to CRS alone versus CRS+HIPEC, with overall survival as the primary endpoint and analysis of prognostic factors.',
    results_detail: 'Median OS 11.0 vs 6.5 months (HR 0.73, p=0.046) favouring CRS+HIPEC, with comparable serious adverse-event rates between arms. Multivariable analysis identified completeness of cytoreduction, low peritoneal cancer index, more than six HIPEC-relevant favourable factors and absence of systemic metastases as predictors of better survival. This provided the first randomised evidence that HIPEC adds survival benefit to cytoreduction in gastric carcinomatosis.',
    practice_change: 'Provided proof-of-principle that HIPEC can extend survival in gastric peritoneal metastases and anchored Chinese consensus guidelines and subsequent confirmatory Western trials (GASTRICHIP, GASTRIPEC-I). While later Western RCTs were negative, this trial remains the pivotal randomised reference underpinning ongoing investigation and highly selected use of CRS+HIPEC in gastric carcinomatosis.',
    criticisms: 'Small (n=68), single-centre trial with short absolute survival and modest statistical significance (p=0.046). Predates modern systemic regimens (e.g. FLOT) and lacks central review. The benefit was not reproduced in the larger Western GASTRICHIP RCT, raising questions about generalisability beyond the original population and protocol.',
    evidence_level: 'Ib',
    study_type: 'RCT',
    full_citation: 'Yang XJ, Huang CQ, Suo T, Mei LJ, Yang GL, Cheng FL, Zhou YF, Xiong B, Yonemura Y, Li Y. Cytoreductive surgery and hyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy improves survival of patients with peritoneal carcinomatosis from gastric cancer: final results of a phase III randomized clinical trial. Ann Surg Oncol. 2011;18(6):1575-1581. PMID: 21431408.',
