    design: 'European multicentre, randomised, phase 3 trial in eight tertiary hospitals (Netherlands, Sweden, Finland, Denmark). 1:1 randomisation stratified by centre, histological subtype and extent of peritoneal metastases. Recruitment Nov 2017–Aug 2024. NCT03348150. Closed early for futility after an unplanned commissioned interim analysis.',
    results_detail: '102 participants (51 per group). Median age 60; 57% men. Median follow-up 67 months. Median OS 16.6 months (95% CI 14.1–21.9) with systemic therapy alone vs 15.7 months (95% CI 11.4–25.5) with gastrectomy+CRS+HIPEC; HR 1.10 (95% CI 0.69–1.74; p=0.70). Grade ≥3 adverse events 20% (standard) vs 42% (experimental); serious adverse events 6% vs 44%. Three treatment-related deaths, all in the surgical arm (ARDS, anastomotic leakage, bleeding), within 100 days.',
    practice_change: 'Practice-defining negative trial: it argues against gastrectomy + CRS+HIPEC as a survival-improving strategy for gastric cancer with limited peritoneal metastases, reinforcing systemic therapy as standard and cautioning against the substantial added morbidity/mortality of the aggressive surgical approach.',
